Mock Interview Answer: Design Jira (10–15 minutes)
1. Clarify Requirements (1–2 minutes)
Before jumping into the design, I would like to clarify the requirements.

Functional Requirements
I assume the system should support:
  1-Users can create projects
  2-Users can create issues (task, bug, story)
  3-Assign issues to team members
  4-Update issue status
  5-Add comments and attachments
  6-Search and filter issues
  7-Notifications for updates
  8-Issue workflows (To Do → In Progress → Done)

Optional features if time allows:
Scrum / Kanban boards
Sprint management
Reports

Non-Functional Requirements
  1-The system should support:
  2-High availability (99.9%)
  3-Low latency (<200ms API)
  4-Scalability for millions of issues
  5-Strong consistency for issue updates
  6-Secure access control

2. Estimate Scale (1 minute)
Let's assume:
  Users = 10 million
  Daily active users = 1 million
  Issues created per user daily:
    5 issues/day
  Total issues created per day:
    1M × 5 = 5M issues/day
  Average issue size:
    2KB metadata
  Storage per year:
    5M × 365 × 2KB ≈ 3.6TB/year
  So the system needs to handle large data storage and heavy reads.

3. High Level Architecture (2 minutes)
The system will follow a microservice architecture.
Architecture components:
    
    Client (Web/Mobile)
            |
        Load Balancer
            |
         API Gateway
            |
    --------------------------------
    Auth Service
    Project Service
    Issue Service
    Workflow Service
    Search Service
    Notification Service
    --------------------------------
            |
         Databases
            |
 Cache / Queue / Search Engine
4. Core Services
  1. Auth Service
      Handles:
      Login
      Authentication
      Authorization
      Supports role-based access control.
  
  2. Project Service
      Handles:
      Create project
      Add members
      Manage project settings
  
  3. Issue Service
      This is the core service.
      Responsibilities:
      Create issue
      Update issue
      Assign issue
      Add comments
      Change status
  
  4. Workflow Service
  Controls issue transitions.
  Example workflow:
  
      Backlog
         ↓
      To Do
         ↓
      In Progress
         ↓
      Code Review
         ↓
      Done
      
      Admin users can configure workflows.
  
  5. Search Service
    Searching issues by:
    status
    assignee
    project
    priority
    label
  We can use Elasticsearch for fast filtering.
6. Notification Service
  Triggers alerts when:
  issue assigned
  comment added
  status changed
  Uses event queue for asynchronous notifications.

5. Database Design (2 minutes)
  A relational database like PostgreSQL is suitable because:
  strong relationships
  transactions
  structured data
  Users Table
